{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18144"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18144"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.05,0.09,0.09,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10858"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the intrinsic muscles of the hand is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Palmar interossei adduct the fingers, acting on three digits","Palmar interossei abduct the fingers, acting on four digits","Dorsal interossei adduct the fingers, acting on three digits","Dorsal interossei abduct the fingers, acting on three digits","Palmar interossei adduct the fingers, acting on four digits"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalmar interossei\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are responsible for adducting the fingers towards the middle finger. There are three palmar interossei muscles, each acting on the index, ring, and little fingers. The thumb does not have a palmar interosseous muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal interossei\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are responsible for abducting the fingers away from the middle finger. There are four dorsal interossei muscles, each acting on the index, middle, and ring fingers. The little finger has its own abductor muscle, the abductor digiti minimi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the function of these muscles is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions that affect hand movement and dexterity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The palmar interossei muscles are responsible for adducting the fingers towards the middle finger.","The dorsal interossei muscles are responsible for abducting the fingers away from the middle finger.","There are three palmar interossei muscles and four dorsal interossei muscles in the hand."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawye